\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$f_c$\end{document} above which the disease dies out without ever infecting an extensive fraction of the population. The threshold can be seen to be both highly dependent on whether social distancing is in place and on the distribution strategy for the vaccine. Regardless of social distancing, the targeted strategy far outperforms the uniform one and is able to suppress the epidemic when just a small fraction of the population has been vaccinated. The performance of the uniform strategy improves much more gradually as the fraction of vaccinated individuals increases. For the targeted strategies, the critical vaccination thresholds are estimated as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
