\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$^2$\end{document} square), but the converse is not true; it is possible for two devices to be arbitrarily close to one another and not have that interaction count as a contact. A more accurate (but harder to implement) approach would have been to consider the devices to be in contact if they came within some threshold \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$\ell_2$\end{document} distance of one another.

sec.p:
Networks for which the tail of the degree distribution obeys a strict power law are known as scale-free networks [33]. Many real-world networks across a large variety of disciplines have been claimed to be scale-free, although the actual prevalence of truly scale-free networks has been challenged [34]. In the context of epidemiological modelling, scale-free networks have been observed in the location–location contact network (as opposed to the person-person contact network) [35]. The extent to which the contact networks are scale-free can be assessed by performing a statistical fit to asymptotic power-law behaviour [36], which is described by a probability mass function of the form \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$p(k) = k^{-\alpha}$\end{document} for \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$k > k_{\text{min}}$\end{document}, where \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$k_{\text{min}}$\end{document} indicates the start of the tail, and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$\alpha > 1$\end{document} is the power-law exponent. We performed such a fit using the powerlaw Python package [37], which takes into account the various subtleties regarding the statistical significance of putative heavy-tailed behaviour in finite data sets that was analyzed in [36].

When we fit both parameters \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$(\alpha, k_{\text{min}})$\end{document} to the degree distribution of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$G_{\text{pre}}$\end{document}, the optimal \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$k_{\text{min}}$\end{document} value is 140, which implies that the tail only includes 0.4% of the nodes, indicating that the fit should not be trusted. If instead of fitting \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$k_{\text{min}}$\end{document} we instead specify it to be the median, so that the tail contains 50% of the nodes, then we find that the data are better described by a log-normal distribution than by a power-law, but both distributions are better fits than an exponentially bounded distribution. Thus, while not power-law, the tail is indeed described by a heavy-tailed distribution (though we note that there are various definitions of the term ‘heavy-tailed’, and some of these exclude log-normal distributions).

We then fit both parameters \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$(\alpha, k_{\text{min}})$\end{document} to the degree distribution of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$G_{\text{post}}$\end{document}. The optimal \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$k_{\text{min}}$\end{document} value is 21, which implies that the tail only includes 3.5% of the nodes. This is a rather small proportion, although perhaps not small enough to discard the fit. Interestingly, this fraction is similar in scale to the critical vaccination fraction for the targeted vaccination strategy considered above, which indicates that the heavy-tailed regime includes enough of the high-connectivity nodes to determine the critical vaccination threshold. The fitted value of the exponent is \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$\alpha = 3.57$\end{document}, and a pairwise comparison analysis concludes that the power-law fit better describes the data than a fit to either a log-normal distribution or an exponential distribution. We also considered a fit with \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
